Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant John T Belsha in court with attorney Jeffrey J. Morgan.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin. 

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.

The Court sentenced defendant to serve 9  MONTHS in the House of Corrections, consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 2 days time served.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 1 YEAR with the following conditions:
-Restitution set at $7,090 payable to Paul F.  Attorney informs the Court that he has this amount in his trust account and will forward to Paul F. 
-Defendant to pay Court costs and all applicable surcharges and assessments are to be collected during term of probation
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge to be collected during term of probation; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended
-Follow all rules of probation
-Pay all supervision fees; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment 
-Cooperate with agent
-Obtain/maintain employment
-Anger management assessment; cooperate with any treatment deemed appropriate
-No contact with Paul F.
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzers
-No alcohol or controlled substances
-Perform 50 hours of community service 

Filed, Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief
received and filed

As to the amended count:  Defendant changes his plea to NO CONTEST.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, jury instructions and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 19.
Filed with the Court:  State's victim impact statement and letters from counseling on behalf of defendant

Defendant John T Belsha in court with attorney Jeffrey J. Morgan.  Ronald Dague appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  To be filed by the State, original amended information.  Defendant acknowledges amendment of information, and pleads not guilty.
